# Android Development Rules for Cursor

## Project Context
This is an Android project using Java with the following setup:
- Package: com.example.h_cas
- Target SDK: 36, Min SDK: 24
- Java 11 compatibility
- Uses AndroidX libraries and Material Design
- Gradle build system

## Coding Standards
- Follow Android Java conventions
- Use meaningful variable and method names
- Add proper JavaDoc comments for public methods
- Handle null checks appropriately
- Use proper Android lifecycle methods

## File Organization
- Keep activities in the main/java package structure
- Place layouts in res/layout/
- Put drawable resources in res/drawable/
- Store string resources in res/values/strings.xml
- Use proper resource naming conventions (snake_case)

## Android-Specific Guidelines
- Always check for null when working with Views
- Use proper Context handling
- Implement proper lifecycle management
- Follow Material Design principles
- Use ConstraintLayout for complex layouts
- Handle edge-to-edge display properly

## Build and Development
- This project uses Gradle for building
- Use Android Studio for running/debugging
- Use Cursor for code editing and development
- Keep build.gradle dependencies up to date

## Common Patterns
- Use findViewById with proper null checks
- Implement proper error handling
- Use proper threading for background tasks
- Follow Android's recommended architecture patterns










